===Glyph origin===
{{Han etyl}}
{{liushu|p}} – a snake's tongue emerging upwards from a mouth ({{zh-l|*口}}).

Evolution:
* '''Oracle bone script''': Originally a mouth + a forked snake tongue. Later variants added a horizontal stroke at the base to indicate location, which often evolved into a second fork (double-forked).
* '''Bronze script''' (Late Shang / Early Western Zhou): Standardized with four dots symmetrically placed between the double forks and the mouth. 
* '''Later''': The dots disappeared, simplifying into the modern form.

Compare {{och-l|舌|tr=*m-lat}} and {{och-l|蛇|tr=*m-laj|snake}}. See also [[言]], [[音]] and [[告]]. Unrelated to [[舍]], in which it represents a hut.

===Etymology 1===
From {{inh|zh|sit-pro|*s/m-l(j)a-t||tongue}}; compare {{cog|mrd|मेलेट||tongue|tr=melet}}, {{cog|kac|shing'''let'''||tongue}} (STEDT; {{zh-ref|Schuessler, 2009}}). The reconstruction of a complex initial {{m|och||*m(ə)-l-}} in {{cog|och|-}} is based on evidence from the softened initial in {{cog|zhx-min-pro|-}} as well as {{cog|hmx-pro|*mblet||tongue}} ({{zh-ref|Schuessler, 2007}}; {{zh-ref|Baxter and Sagart, 2014}}).

Alternatively, {{zh-ref|Schuessler (2007)}}, reconstructing the {{cog|och|-}} minimally as {{m|och||*m-lat}}, derives it from {{och-l|舐|tr=*m-leʔ|to lick}} + {{m|och||*-t|nominal suffix for natural objects|sc=Latn}}, literally “licker”.

